Finding ID    : F-04
Severity      : MEDIUM
OWASP Ref     : API4:2023 — Unrestricted Resource Consumption
APIs Tested   : JSONPlaceholder & ReqRes
Endpoint      : All endpoints
Date Discovered: Mon, 27 Apr 2026
Analyst       : CrazyCoder

--------------------------------------------------------------
DESCRIPTION
--------------------------------------------------------------

Five consecutive GET requests were sent to the /users endpoint with a
200-millisecond pause between each. None of the five responses contained
any rate-limiting headers. No HTTP 429 Too Many Requests response was
received.

The absence of rate limiting means there is no server-side control
preventing automated abuse: data scraping, credential stuffing, or
a denial-of-service flood.

NOTE: Test was limited to exactly 5 requests at ethical scope. This is an
observational check — no flooding was performed.

--------------------------------------------------------------
PROOF OF CONCEPT  (Evidence)
--------------------------------------------------------------

TEST PROCEDURE:
  5 sequential GET requests to /users with 200ms delay between each.

REQUEST/RESPONSE LOG:
  [1] GET /users  -->  200 OK  (time: 0ms)
  [2] GET /users  -->  200 OK  (time: 200ms)
  [3] GET /users  -->  200 OK  (time: 400ms)
  [4] GET /users  -->  200 OK  (time: 600ms)
  [5] GET /users  -->  200 OK  (time: 800ms)

RESPONSE HEADER AUDIT (all 5 responses):
  X-RateLimit-Limit       -->  NOT PRESENT
  X-RateLimit-Remaining   -->  NOT PRESENT
  Retry-After             -->  NOT PRESENT
  RateLimit-Limit         -->  NOT PRESENT
  X-RateLimit-Reset       -->  NOT PRESENT

NO HTTP 429 response received across any of the 5 requests.

EXPECTED: Rate-limit headers present; 429 returned when limit exceeded
ACTUAL:   Unlimited requests accepted — MEDIUM FINDING

--------------------------------------------------------------
BUSINESS IMPACT
--------------------------------------------------------------

1. Data scraping: An automated script can harvest the entire dataset in
   seconds, bypassing any intended access controls completely.

2. Credential stuffing: Login endpoints without rate limiting can be
   targeted with millions of username/password pairs from leaked credential
   databases, leading to account takeovers at scale.

3. Denial of Service: A flood of requests can exhaust server resources and
   CPU, taking the API offline for all legitimate users.

4. Cost amplification: In cloud deployments (AWS, GCP, Azure), each API
   call may trigger billable database queries or ML inference. Unthrottled
   traffic creates unbounded cost exposure.

--------------------------------------------------------------
REMEDIATION  (Priority: SHORT-TERM — fix within 30 days)
--------------------------------------------------------------

Step 1: Implement rate limiting at the API gateway or reverse proxy layer.
        This applies globally without modifying application code.
        Nginx example:
        limit_req_zone $binary_remote_addr zone=api:10m rate=100r/m;
        limit_req zone=api burst=20 nodelay;

Step 2: Apply differentiated limits by endpoint sensitivity:
        - Authentication endpoints: 10 requests/minute per IP
        - Public data endpoints:    100 requests/minute per IP
        - Admin endpoints:          5 requests/minute per IP

Step 3: Return HTTP 429 Too Many Requests with a Retry-After header
        so well-behaved clients can back off appropriately:
        HTTP/1.1 429 Too Many Requests
        Retry-After: 60
        Content-Type: application/json
        {"error": "Rate limit exceeded. Please retry after 60 seconds."}

Step 4: Apply both IP-based and token-based limits independently.
        Neither mechanism alone can be bypassed by the other method.

